==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Minx
<hw>Minx</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. of Low
German origin; cf. LG. <ets>minsk</ets> wench, jade, hussy, D.
<ets>mensch</ets>; prop. the same word as D. & G. <ets>mensch</ets> man,
human being, OHG. <ets>mennisco</ets>, AS. <ets>mennisc</ets>, fr.
<ets>man</ets>. See <er>Man</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pert or a
wanton girl.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A she puppy; a pet dog.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Udall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minx</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Minx
<hw>Minx</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mink</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The mink; -- called also <cref>minx
otter</cref>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 928 --></p>

